->to enable async write @EnableAsync in main class . so spring will create beans for sync classes
->just annotate method with @async- to enable asynchronous execution for that method
->Thread.currentThread.getName() -> will display exact thread name
->ThreadPollTaskExecutor(sprinf) is an wrapper class for ThreadPoolExecutor(plain java )
->

->disadvantages of defaultExecutor is more memory usage , thread exhaustion , max latency , underutilization of threads
->to overcome this we need to create our own threadpooltaskexecutor. other wise spring chooses above default executor
->by using threadpooltaskexecutor we can set thread name , max aue size , min threads , maxcore threads .
->we can create our own threadpoolexecutor instead of threadpooltaskexecutor
->if we create threadpoolexecutor  on our own then java use our executor instead of threadpooltaskexecutor
->the method which is annotated with async must be public because aop is involved
->we cant annotate the same method  with both async and transactional.
->if we want transactional , async thn call async method from main class and call transactional method for async method .
->if any error happened then transaction can roll back and also we can maintain asynchronization
->
